Love this app! I'm a minimalist, wanted a screen with no icons whatsoever, here's how:  Set CircleLauncher's transparency to 100%, and set Label color to a highly-contrasting color from your background image.  I set my widget label to say, "As you wish, my lord", positioned right where my thumb would naturally go.  There were only two icons I couldn't remove; one was a flashlight widget, I solved that problem by downloading ASUS FlashLight app instead, which could then go into CircleLauncher like any other app.  The other was an ES File Explorer shortcut to my user folder.  For this, I created a new screen, set the shortcut's icon to 5 x 5, used a favorite photo as the icon, and used Carousel screen swipe effect.  Now, I have two screens with no icons, only the Android app button and the status bar.  Suggested (really cool) combination of settings in CircleLauncher:  Launcher style Circle, Show centered,  Opening animation Roll in from top, Speed 0.5, Closing animation Bounce, Speed 0.5, and in More settings, Fullscreen without the status bar.  The app has the ability to Backup configuration.  I hope the Restore will work - but setting everything up only took me about 10 minutes.
Small learning curve. Well worth the trouble to learn it though.

While there's a lot of flexibility and tweaking one can do to make it just the way you want, layout is at least somewhat static in that you are stuck with a specific grid of icons (in the square config) and you can't control that grid layout much except to make all icons smaller/larger, shift the entire grid one way or another, etc.  You can't control how many rows or columns there are for example, let alone have empty "slots" within that grid.  But in general, it's a great app, especially with the new functionality and I'm hopeful that future updates will see even more.

Won't Die!!!! Circle Launcher has always been a very well put together application, and I've always found it to be a great utility and addition to the phones I've owned.  But I cannot give it five stars, I do not want to even give it 1 star, but with Android's rating system I have no other choice. My vehemence for it lies in the simple fact that I cannot kill it. I go into my "Running Processes" on my phone, and even though I'm currently not using the app, nor have I for quite a long time, well there it sits running, eating up precious resources.	This would be understandable if I was using it, but as I've said, I'm not. I select it in the menu for running applications, click "Kill", and absolutely nothing happens! I repeat this futile step exhaustively, and it does absolutely no good, the app just will not die! I have no patience for an app and it's developer, if they can't code an app correctly, and keep it from stealing valuable system resources, while it slows down my phone. If this is fixed, I'll amend my review.

Users are forced to use the standard icons for apps when using this widget. Got an app with a hideous standard icon? Unfortunately, your Circle Launcher will now be marred by that hideous icon.You won't be able to customize it with a user specified image. Poor.  Moreover, folders / app groups cannot be included on the "circle". Each individual app must have its own slot on the widget. This effectively means the user desiring to launch a large number of apps must either have overpopulated Circles or multiple smaller Circles.  A ideal design would allow the user to simply pick apps and/or folders directly from their home screen, complete with their current custom icons.
